{"id": 100547, "acmi_id": "", "title": "Glass cinema slides", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "glass-cinema-slides", "creator_credit": "", "credit_line": "", "headline_credit": "c. 1920s-1940s", "record_type": "group", "type": "Object", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "first_production_date": null, "brief_description": "<p>These glass slides advertise films that charted the change from silent to sound cinema, as well as the changing face of cinema when the Motion Picture Production Code was established.</p>", "constellations_primary": [{"id": 216, "name": "Wearing the pants, ladies who lead", "description": "The pre-code 1932 feature, <i>A Bill of Divorcement</i>, a glass cinema slide of which features in the glass cinema slide display, stars John Barrymore and Katharine Hepburn in her screen debut."}], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>Glass cinema slides</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>c. 1920s-1940s</p>", "description": "<p>Hollywood studios spent a lot of money transitioning to talkies. To recoup the cost, they produced salacious films to attract big audiences. People certainly responded – including conservative groups, who pressured studios to protect family values. The Motion Picture Production Code was established in 1930 as a response but wasn’t enforced until 1934. These glass slides advertise films that charted the change from silent to sound cinema, including <i>A Bill of Divorcement</i> (1932), which flouted the production code by exploring a marriage breakdown, as well as John Ford’s <i>The World Moves On</i> (1934), the first film to receive a Motion Pictures Producers and Distributors of America (now MPAA) certificate under the new Production Code.</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>Hollywood studios spent a lot of money